AB  - Suppose that a white American asks a Hispanic American, "Where are you from?" and that the Hispanic American response "Florida." Suppose, further, that the white American then insists, "But where are you really from?". Many people take this to be a paradigmatic example of a microaggression; but they seem to disagree about what features of this action make it count as such. Some seem to hold that what makes this a microaggression is that in asking "But where are you really from?" the white American sends a harmful message to the Hispanic American: for example, that Hispanics are not truly American or that they do not belong in the US. Others seem to hold that what makes this a microaggression is that the white American's motivation for insisting "But where are you really from?" is an implicit, unconscious prejudice about the Hispanic American: for example, that Hispanics are not truly American, or that Hispanics do not belong in the US. Others, still, seem to maintain that this is an example of microaggression if, as a result of being asked "But where are you really from?", the Hispanic American experiences negative feelings such as of not belonging or of being abnormal. Finally, some seem to hold that microaggression is not about a harmful message, nor about the psychological states of the perpetrator, nor about the psychological states of the victim; rather, it is about reproducing an oppressive social order through repeated dismissive, alienating, and discriminatory treatment of people who lack power and privilege in our society. On this view, asking a minority individual "But where are you really from?" fits into a pattern of alienating and discriminatory treatment that reproduces the oppression of people who already lack power in our society.
